  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "To calculate the pH of a solution from the hydronium-ion concentration \\([H_3O^+]\\), you can use the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log[H_3O^+]\n\\]\n\nIn this case, the hydronium-ion concentration is given as \\(1 \\times 10^{-12} \\, \\text{M}\\).\n\nNow we can calculate the pH:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log(1 \\times 10^{-12})\n\\]\n\nUsing the properties of logarithms:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -(-12) = 12\n\\]\n\nThus, the pH of the solution is **12**.",
